<h4>
    Circular Geometry Basics
</h4>

<ul class = 'principleList'>
    <li>
        A circle is made of all points equidistant from a single point.
    </li>
    <li>
        The distance from the center of the circle to the outside is the <strong>radius</strong> (\( r \)).
    </li>
    <li>
        The distance from one end of the the circle to the other that
        goes through the center is called the <strong>diameter</strong>(\( d \)).
        The diameter is twice the radius: \( d = 2r \).
    </li>
    <li>
        The length around the entire circle is called the <strong>circumference</strong>(\( C \)).
    </li>
    <li>
        The circumference divided by the diameter is the same number for every circle,
        called \( \pi \) and equal to approximately 3.14.
    </li>
    <li>
        \( \frac{C}{d} = \pi \)
    </li>
    <li>
        \( C = 2 \pi r \)
    </li>
</ul>

