<h4>
    Finding Both Linear and Angular Speed of an object moving around a circle.
</h4>

<p>
    If you have already learned about <a href = '/unit/rotational_motion/rotational_kinematics'>rotational kinematics</a>,
    then you know that there is another way to describe the motion of an object moving in a circle
    called its <emph>angular speed</emph>.
    It is <emph>very important</emph> not to mix the two up!
    I included a couple of questions here on finding both linear and angular speed to help make sure you see the difference every time.
</p>

<p>
    There are two different ways to describe the speed of an object moving in a circle:
</p>
<ul class = 'principleList'>
    <li>
        An objects <strong>linear speed</strong> is the distance it moves
        divided by the time.
    </li>
    <li>
        An object's <strong>angular speed</strong> represents how many radians
        the object moves around the circle divided by time.
    </li>
</ul>

